<article>
    <h1>What other ju&#xAD;ris&#xAD;dic&#xAD;tions have done</h1>
    <h2>Some coun&#xAD;tries have phased out the use of big ban&#xAD;knotes, as they have been as&#xAD;so&#xAD;ci&#xAD;ated with a range of fi&#xAD;nan&#xAD;cial crimes</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201104/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-04"><time>2020-11-04</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>EUROPE</p>
    <p>The Euro­pean Cen­tral Bank an­nounced in 2016 that it would stop is­su­ing the €500 ban­knote, not­ing that the ban­knote could fa­cil­i­tate il­licit ac­tiv­i­ties. All 19 na­tional cen­tral banks in the euro area have stopped is­su­ing the ban­knote, dubbed the “Bin Laden” note after ter­ror­ist Osama bin Laden, since April last year. High­est-de­nom­i­na­tion ban­knote: €200 UNITED STATES</p>
    <p>Cur­rency notes in de­nom­i­na­tions of $500, $1,000 and $5,000 were dis­con­tin­ued in 1969, due to a “lack of use”. High­est-de­nom­i­na­tion ban­knote:</p>
    <p>US$100</p>
    <p>MALAYSIA</p>
    <p>Its cen­tral bank dis­con­tin­ued its RM500 and RM1,000 notes in 1999. High­est-de­nom­i­na­tion ban­knote:</p>
    <p>RM100 CANADA</p>
    <p>The coun­try stopped is­su­ing its $1,000 ban­knotes in 2000 and it will re­move the “le­gal ten­der ” sta­tus of these notes from Jan­uary, as part of its fight against money laun­der­ing and or­gan­ised crime. High­est-de­nom­i­na­tion ban­knote:</p>
    <p>C$100</p>
    <p>BRUNEI</p>
    <p>The coun­try dis­con­tin­ued its $10,000 cur­rency notes on Mon­day, as part of the coun­try ’s com­mit­ment to re­duc­ing the risks of such notes be­ing as­so­ci­ated with fi­nan­cial crimes.</p>
    <p>High­est-de­nom­i­na­tion ban­knote:</p>
    <p>$1,000</p>


